<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-introduction-to-sequences" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Introduction to Sequences</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.6 Sequences and Series
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine nth term in a number sequences
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To identify patterns in ordered lists of numbers and predict subsequent terms in a sequence.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into small groups and provide several number patterns. Guide learners to observe how the terms change from one position to the next and encourage them to explain their reasoning. Ask learners to predict missing terms and discuss whether different patterns can produce different sequences.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add Activity -->
     <activity>
        <p>
            <term>Study the following patterns in Groups</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>2,4,6,8 ...</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>1,4,9,16 ... </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>1,-2,4,-88 ...</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            In each case, state the next two numbers. Share with other groups how you obtained your answers?
        </p>
        
     </activity>


    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        10 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To define a sequence and identify its terms and underlying pattern.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Using the patterns explored during the activity, explain that a sequence is an ordered list of numbers arranged according to a rule. The numbers that make up a sequence are called terms.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Point out that each sequence follows a pattern. In some sequences, a fixed number is added or subtracted from one term to obtain the next term, while in others a term may be multiplied or divided by a constant value.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasize that the position of a term is important. The first term, second term, third term and so on help us describe and analyse a sequence.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Guide learners to use the observed pattern to predict missing terms and determine future terms in a sequence.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            The next two numbers is obtained using some rule. If numbers are arranged in a definite order (following a specific rule), they form a sequence.
        </p>
        <p>
            All the three patterns above are examples of sequences. Each of the numbers in a sequence is called a term. In sequence (i) above the first term is <m>2</m>, the third term is <m>6</m>, and the fifth term is <m>10</m>. For the remaining sequences (ii) and (iii), state the first, third and fifth terms.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <!-- <insight>
    </insight> -->

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each of the following sequences, find the next three terms:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1,3,5,7...</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> 
                            <m>\frac{1}{3},\frac{1}{9},\frac{1}{27}... </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1,8,27... </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>-3,6,-12,...</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To obtain the next term, add <m>2</m> to the preceeding term.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           The next three terms are <m>9, 11, \;\text{and}\; 13</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To obtain the next term, the preceeding term is multiplied by <m>\frac{1}{3} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The next three terms are <m>\frac{1}{81},\frac{1}{243}, \;\text{and}\;\frac{1}{729} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To obtain the <m>n^{th}</m> term, <m>n</m> is cubed.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The next three terms are <m>64, 125, \;\text{and}\; 216 </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The next term is obtained by multiplying the preceeding term by <m>-2</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The next three terms are <m>24, -48, \;\text{and} 96</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <m>n^{th}</m> term of a sequence is given by <m>2n+3</m>, find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           The first term 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The fifth term.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The twelfth term
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For the first term, <m>n=1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting, <m>2\times 1+3 = 5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For the fifth term, <m>n=1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting, <m>2\times 5+3 = 13</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For the twelfth term, <m>n=1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting, <m>2\times 12+3 = 27</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Deduce the general rule in the sequence given below; <m>2,5,8,11 ...</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Notice that the first term is <m>2</m>, the second is <m>5</m>, the third is <m>8</m>, and the forth is <m>11</m>
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Position</cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Term</cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>11</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>?</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Notice that the second, third, and fourth terms can be obtained by adding <m>3</m> to the previous term. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The first term is <m>2</m>, this term can be gotten by expressing <m> 2 = 3 \times 1 -1 </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The second term <m>5 = 3 \times 2 -1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The third term <m>8 = 3 \times 3 -1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The fourth term <m>11 = 3 \times 4 -1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                From this, the <m>n^{th}</m> term is <m>3 \times n - 1 = 3n-1</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>

    

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each of the following sequences, find the terms indicated:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The seventh and twelfth terms.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>0,2,6,12,...</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The seventh and the ninth terms.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{1}{3}, \frac{5}{3}, \frac{9}{3}, \frac{13}{3} ... </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The fifth and eighth terms.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m> \frac{1}{5}, 1, \frac{9}{5}, \frac{13}{5} ... </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>42, 132</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m> \frac{25}{3}, 11 </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{17}{5}, \frac{29}{5} </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Write down the first three terms of a sequence whose <m>n^{th}</m> term is given below:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2n+1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>n^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{n^2+1}{2} </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2n^2-2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2^n+1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2,4,6</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>3,5,7</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1,4,9</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1, \frac{5}{2}, 5 </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>0, 6, 16</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                3,5,9
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Give an expression for the <m>n^{th}</m> term:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>3,6,9,12 ...</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1,3,5,7,9 ...</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>6,11,16 ...</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0,3,8,15 ...</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>3n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2n-1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>5n+1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>n^2-1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <!-- [LP] Add information on how to differentiate  -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide simple number patterns with small positive numbers. Encourage learners to use counting, addition, or subtraction to identify the pattern. Guide them through one term at a time and allow them to discuss their ideas with a partner before sharing with the class.
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide more complex sequences involving multiplication, division, or alternating patterns. Challenge learners to create their own sequences, identify the rule, and ask other groups to determine the next terms.
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>

            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
